  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Christopher Marsh's work on the best-selling ballads and their imagery in seventeenth-century England has garnered notable academic attention, as evidenced by its 18 citations in various scholarly venues, including The Economic History Review and Cambridge University Press eBooks. The research's engagement with historical discourse illustrates its significant role in the study of cultural practices of the time.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The article by Christopher Marsh, titled \"Best-Selling Ballads and their Pictures in Seventeenth-Century England,\" demonstrates a strong academic impact with 18 citations recorded across multiple scholarly resources. Notably, leading citations stem from reputable venues such as Cambridge University Press eBooks, which emphasizes the work's relevance and integration into ongoing research discussions within the historical and cultural studies domain.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The contribution of this research is further solidified by its institutional backing from Queen's University Belfast. This affiliation not only lends credibility to the work but also situates it within a broader geographical context, primarily within the United Kingdom where the majority of citations originate. This indicates a localized yet impactful academic discourse centered around Marsh's findings, particularly in the exploration of cultural artifacts like ballads.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Although there are no public mentions on platforms such as Wikipedia or Reddit, the significant number of citations suggests that the article is being meaningfully engaged with by scholars in related fields. This scholarly attention is demonstrated by the diverse types of citing works, including book chapters, articles, and dissertations, indicating that Marsh's analysis is proliferating through various formats of academic discourse and catalyzing new lines of inquiry.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Overall, Christopher Marsh\u2019s investigation into the interplay between ballads and their imagery enriches the understanding of seventeenth-century English culture. The established downstream reuse of his work, evidenced by its citations across numerous academic outputs, underscores its foundational role in ongoing research and highlights the importance of historical ballads in reflecting societal values and cultural narratives during that period.</p>",
